Raw dev notes -- The Great Side Project Sprawl of April 7th

Okay, so this past week, or really, this *day*, was a bit of a whirlwind. I basically dumped a ton of nascent ideas and existing local projects into version control. It's less about one big project and more about a snapshot of my brain on a particularly prolific day. The "why" is simple: I had a bunch of ideas bubbling, some existing scripts I wanted to track, and a strong urge to just *start* things, especially with all the new AI tech out there. It's my personal playground, a place to experiment without the pressure of a client or a deadline.

What actually got done? Well, a lot of "initial commits" for starters! That's a milestone in itself, getting these ideas out of my head and onto a repo. Beyond just starting, there was a significant push into the LLM space. I kicked off `claude-rag-export` and `claude-sessions-export`, which are all about getting data *out* of LLM sessions, consolidating it, and prepping it for RAG (Retrieval Augmented Generation) pipelines. This involved writing scripts to pull out session data, metadata, and other bits and pieces, then structuring it. Similarly, `Outlook-MailMiner` and `RHGroupMeetingTranscriber` both got `CLAUDE.md` files and some initial research/source code, pointing towards using LLMs to process emails and meeting transcripts. It's all about trying to leverage these models for information extraction and synthesis.

On the more established project front, the `Synagogue Display System` got some love with updated screenshots, new emoji fonts (because who doesn't love emojis?), and better handling of session data and title images. It was a nice little UI/UX refresh. The `Shipping Tracking Dashboard` also saw some solid progress, adding Python automation, documentation, actual dashboards, and monitoring scripts – turning it into a much more robust system for tracking packages. A few other projects like `hebrew-youtube-index-archive` and `wordpress-to-rag-pipeline` got minor chore updates, like adding author credits or normalizing line endings. And `powershell-scripts` was just a general sync of my utility scripts.

What was hard or surprising? Honestly, the sheer volume of *starting* things. It felt like a dam broke. While exciting, it also highlights my "shiny object syndrome." The challenge with the LLM stuff is always the data wrangling – getting the input just right, extracting the output cleanly, and then figuring out how to consolidate it all in a meaningful way. It's less about the LLM itself and more about the plumbing around it. Also, managing repo size, as hinted by the "exclude large binaries" in the Synagogue Display System, is always a minor annoyance. It's easy to forget about until you hit a limit.

Personally, it felt like a burst of creative energy. A bit overwhelming, but also incredibly energizing to just dive into so many different ideas. It's a reminder that I love the exploration phase, the initial spark of a new project. The lesson here is probably about balancing that initial enthusiasm with the discipline to follow through, but for now, I'm just enjoying the ride. It connects to my growth by pushing me to explore new tech (LLMs are still relatively new territory for me in terms of building full pipelines) and to better organize my scattered thoughts into actual codebases.

Next up: Pick one or two of these LLM projects to really dig into and build out.
